  <description type="morphology">Leaf blades broadly elliptic to elliptic-ovate, 4–7 cm (length/width = 1.2), conspicuously concavo-convex, base rounded to broadly cuneate, lobe sinuses often shallow. Stamens 8–10. Pomes usually oblong. 2n = 51, 68.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Flowering May; fruiting Sep–Oct.</description>
  <description type="habitat">Brush, woodland margins, fencerows, overgrown pastures;</description>
  <description type="elevation">10–300 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">Ont., Que.; Conn., Ill., Ind., Mass., Mich., Minn., N.H., N.Y., Ohio, Pa., R.I., Vt., Wis.</description>
  <discussion>Variety pringlei is found throughout much of the range of the species, just reaching Quebec, but is absent in Virginia and North Carolina. Extreme forms are very distinct in appearance with their strikingly convex, broadly elliptic, usually shallowly incised leaves and often oblong fruit. Intermediates with var. coccinea are common.</discussion>
